<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1927-04-15T17:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1927-04-15T17:00:00-05:00" n="173" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d173">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00 Nanking/77: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1927-04-15T17:00:00-05:00"><hi rend="italic">April 15,
                                        1927—5 p.m.</hi></date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>164. Lockhart’s 17 to Legation, April 14, 3 p.m. For the present
                            Department will make no public comment with regard to note and would
                            desire that Legation make no public comment in Peking. Please cable us
                            your comments and also information as to any textual differences in the
                            replies made by Eugene Chen to the several Powers as well as the
                            reaction in Peking.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
